    Humans assume sheep are simple. Sheep assume humans are inscrutable. Neither has direct access to the other’s internal world. Intelligence is bounded by its sensors and priors.
3. Stories as cognitive training.
    The detective novels aren’t entertainment—they become software. The shepherd accidentally trains the sheep in causal reasoning. Fiction changes future inference.
4. Collective intelligence.
    No single sheep is likely brilliant enough to solve the mystery. Different personalities contribute different heuristics. The flock becomes smarter than any individual.
5. Compression and shared language.
    The sheep probably develop shorthand, nicknames, and recurring concepts. That’s how groups compress complexity and coordinate.
6. Blind spots reveal assumptions.
    The mistakes they make will be as informative as the conclusions they reach. Every incorrect hypothesis exposes an implicit model.
7. Identity through perspective.
    The same event has multiple valid descriptions depending on who witnesses it. Truth isn’t just facts—it’s viewpoint plus evidence.
8. Curiosity as survival.
    The mystery isn’t merely intellectual. Solving it matters because it protects the flock. Curiosity has evolutionary value.
9. The danger of overfitting.
    Once the sheep latch onto a theory, they’ll probably interpret every new clue through it until contradictory evidence forces a revision. That’s a universal reasoning trap.
10. Knowledge inheritance.
    The shepherd’s greatest gift isn’t food or shelter. It’s a way of thinking that survives him. His lessons outlive the teacher.

